Date: 27 Nov 2012
Source: Bernama.com Malaysian National News Agency [edited]
http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v6/newsworld.php?id=711761


Zimbabwe Government Misses Anthrax Vaccination Target
-----------------------------------------------------
Lack of funding is preventing the Zimbabwe government from vaccinating cattle against anthrax this year [2012], an official said Monday [26 Nov 2012]. The government had targeted to vaccinate 800 000 cattle throughout the country but only half of the figure had been covered so far, Zimbabwe news agency New Ziana reported.

Veterinary Field Services Department deputy director Dr Chenjerai Njagu said that farmers have been encouraged to buy vaccines using their own resources. "This year the situation has not been good as the division of Veterinary Field Services failed to adequately vaccinate cattle as planned due to vaccine shortage emanating from financial constraints," he said.

The Zimbabwe government is battling to fund its operations due to budgetary constraints, which have left many departments under funded.

This has resulted in the country battling to contain anthrax, which continues to decimate cattle, wild animals, and has left hundreds of people needing treatment after consuming infected animals.

Dr Njangu said the Ministry of Health and Child Welfare was carrying out awareness campaigns to encourage people to report all sudden deaths of livestock and discouraging them from consuming the meat.

