Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Zimbabwe has some 5 million cattle. Last year, 2011, they vaccinated some 23 percent (1 218 872 animals out of 5 334 761 head). In 2009 and 2010 they managed to vaccinate only around 7.5 percent. In previous years it has been about half that number. The trick with controlling anthrax through vaccination is to have good surveillance and then target your vaccination on those areas at highest risk; i.e., within 5 Kms of known previous outbreaks. But if one has not been able to demonstrate the benefits of vaccination, the livestock owners neither report suspect cases nor put their hands in their pockets to pay for their own vaccine, assuming there are supplies available locally. In 2011 anthrax outbreaks were reported in Manicaland, Mashonaland, Mashonaland East, Mashonaland West, Masvingo, Matabeleland North, and Midlands. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1AY4.]
